entry.title: [wptrunner] Add `--reset-results` for baselines
entry.content:
`WPTResultsProcessor` copies `layout-test-results/**/*-actual.txt` to

the corresponding `web_tests/**/*-expected.txt`, then runs the optimizer

at the end of the test run to deduplicate expectations.



The wptrunner and `run_web_tests.py` baseline formatting differ by

insignificant leading/trailing whitespace. To treat them identically,

the optimizer strips such whitespace before hashing the baseline

contents.



Fixed: 1480061

Test: run_wpt_tests.py --reset-results external/wpt/badging

Test: No baselines created.

Test: rm external/wpt/badging/*-expected.txt

Test: Repeat above to create baselines under `platform/linux-chrome/`

entry.title: Revert "Add per-test-case tracing and archive trace output for web_tests"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 8070e3362c2f9efc3ae15b61ecc235acf71b9d52.



Reason for revert: Broke results.html.

> Uncaught SyntaxError: missing ) after argument list - results.html:1039



Original change's description:

> Add per-test-case tracing and archive trace output for web_tests

>

> The existing --enable-tracing argument to run_web_tests.py generates a

> trace that spans the life of the test binary process. Due to the way

> this flag is turned into driver flags, this forces the test runner to

> restart the test binary after every test case. There are a few

> problems:

>

> - There is no way to specify --enable-tracing on a per-test basis.

>

> - Restarting the test binary after every test case is extremely slow.

>

> - Restarting the test binary after every test may suppress failures

> caused by stale state left in the test binary after a test case.

> Historically, this is a significant source of bugs.

>

> - The trace file is not archived by the test runner.

>

> This patch tries to fix all four problems. The trace file created by

> --enable-tracing is now archived. Additionally, the new flag

> --enable-per-test-tracing allows tracing to be enabled on a per-test

> basis; it does not force additional test binary restarts; and its

> output is also archived. The two flags can be used in combination

> without any problem.

>

> The new python class variable Port.TESTS_TO_TRACE offers a convenient

> way to generate profiles for a limited set of tests when running on

> the bots.

>

entry.title: [SAA] Prototyping non-cookie extension (Part 7: blob storage)
entry.content:
The Storage Access API provides access to unpartitioned cookies in

third-party contexts. This CL is part of a series to extend that access

to non-cookie storage/communication mechanisms.



This CL only includes blob storage functions as a next step for

the new access. We want to be deliberate adding new mechanisms

since we need good testing and security review here.



All access is restricted to experimental contexts for now, no stable

access or origin trial timeline has been published.



Explainer:

https://arichiv.github.io/saa-non-cookie-storage/



Intent to Prototype:

https://groups.google.com/a/chromium.org/g/blink-dev/c/inRN8tI49O0



Part 1: local/session storage

Part 2: indexeddb

Part 3: web locks

Part 4: cache storage

Part 5: origin private file system

Part 6: quota

Part 7: blob storage

Part 8: broadcast channel

Part 9: shared worker



Bug: 1484966

entry.title: Fix test LacrosExtensionAppsControllerTest.LaunchPinnedApp
entry.content:
This fixes a race condition in the mentioned test.



Key steps in the test:

1. Test (Lacros) launches the app and waits until the shelf (Ash) knows

about the app.

2. Test pins the app.

3. Test closes the app window.

4. Test waits until Ash says the window is gone.

5. Test launches the app via the shelf (Ash).

6. Test waits for the app window.



The test occasionally times out in step (6). Here's what happens in

these runs:



When step (4) is executed, exo has not yet processed the Ash part of

step (3). In fact, exo has not even shown the window from step (1) as

it's still waiting for content. Because the window isn't shown, step (4)

immediately finishes. In step (5) the invisible window is found,

bypassing the actual launch of the app. Instead, Ash tries to activate

the existing window, but there is still no content. Moreover, between

(5) and (6) Ash performs the window destruction triggered via Wayland

in step (3), so the test times out in step (6).



Fix this by waiting for the app window before step (3).

entry.title: Add per-test-case tracing and archive trace output for web_tests
entry.content:
The existing --enable-tracing argument to run_web_tests.py generates a

trace that spans the life of the test binary process. Due to the way

this flag is turned into driver flags, this forces the test runner to

restart the test binary after every test case. There are a few

problems:



- There is no way to specify --enable-tracing on a per-test basis.



- Restarting the test binary after every test case is extremely slow.



- Restarting the test binary after every test may suppress failures

caused by stale state left in the test binary after a test case.

Historically, this is a significant source of bugs.



- The trace file is not archived by the test runner.



This patch tries to fix all four problems. The trace file created by

--enable-tracing is now archived. Additionally, the new flag

--enable-per-test-tracing allows tracing to be enabled on a per-test

basis; it does not force additional test binary restarts; and its

output is also archived. The two flags can be used in combination

without any problem.



The new python class variable Port.TESTS_TO_TRACE offers a convenient

way to generate profiles for a limited set of tests when running on

the bots.

entry.title: Support BFCache eviction with BackgroundResourceFetch feature
entry.content:
When the page receives a HTTP response while it is in BFCache,

MojoURLLoaderClient::BodyBuffer drains the body mojo data pipe to its

buffer. And if the buffered data size exceeds the limit

`max_buffered_bytes_per_process`, the page will be evicted from the

BFCache. This logic was originally introduced by

https://crrev.com/c/2513314 and https://crrev.com/c/2539215.



Currently this logic doesn't work when BackgroundResourceFetch feature

is enabled, because EvictFromBackForwardCacheOnBackground() and

DidBufferLoadWhileInBackForwardCacheOnBackground() of

BackgroundURLLoader::Context is not implemented yet. So this CL

implement these methods and add tests in

BackForwardCacheNetworkLimitBrowserTest.



This cl introduces `update_process_wide_count` argument in

BackForwardCacheLoaderHelper::DidBufferLoadWhileInBackForwardCache()

methods. This argument is needed because BackgroundURLLoader need to

update the BackForwardCacheBufferLimitTracker.total_bytes_buffered_ in

the background thread, and update

LocalDOMWindow.total_bytes_buffered_while_in_back_forward_cache_ in the

main thread.



This CL also changes CreateResourceLoadInfoNotifierWrapper() method

of RenderFrameImpl to pass a kNetworking type task runner to the

constructor of ResourceLoadInfoNotifierWrapper. Without this,

ResourceLoadInfoNotifierWrapper may send an IPC to the browser process

even when the page is in the BFCache which will be recorded as

"BackForwardCache.UnexpectedRendererToBrowserMessage.InterfaceName" by

BackForwardCacheMessageFilter::WillDispatch, and EXPECT_THAT() in the

BackForwardCacheBrowserTest's destructor fails.



BackForwardCacheNetworkLimitBrowserTests are already flaky even without

this cl, so setting `Validate-Test-Flakiness: Skip`.

entry.title: [IdleTimeout] Adding IdleService for IdleTimeout policies
entry.content:
This CL adds the skeleton for idle detection and scheduling the

actions to run when the browser is idle.



The idle service scheduling starts on warm and cold startup and any

tasks are cancelled when the browser is backgrounded.



When the browser times out while foregrounded, the task is scheduled to when idle

timeout can happen. On cold/warm startup a few cases are considered to decide

if actions should run:



1. Browser is started for the first time (last active and idle times

are unknown)

2. The browser never timed out before, but the last active time is known.

In this case we check that current time > last active time + idle threshold

3. Browser was idle then used and became idle again (including background

time). In this case we check that last active time + threshold >

last idle time.

entry.title: Prevent zygote control socket fds being leaked into child processes
entry.content:
If an embedder application executes a program, the spawned child process

inherits the file descriptor of the zygote control socket. The inherited

file descriptor keeps connection alive with the zygote process. The

zygote process won't terminate until the connection is alive.



This means that a child process of an embedder application may keep the

zygote running if they don't close the control socket's file descriptor

explicitly.



To prevent this, create the control socket pair with SOCK_CLOEXEC flag

for implicitly closing it in the child process when an exec family

function is called.

entry.title: Fix some incompatibilities with std::variant from narrowing
entry.content:
std::variant does not allow narrowing conversions. absl::variant didn't

quite get this right, which means narrowing conversions sometimes sneak

in.



The main non-obvious consequence is that std::variant

cannot be constructed from literals like 0 or 2. Such literals have type

int, and an int may be negative. These ints will not be negative, but

the language has lost this information by the time it calls the

std::variant constructor.



The fix is to write 0u or 2u. Those have type unsigned, which can
